        <type>int</type>
        <definition>int TmrCtrPolledExample</definition>
        <argsstring>(UINTPTR BaseAddr, u8 TmrCtrNumber)</argsstring>
        <name>TmrCtrPolledExample</name>
        <param>
          <type>UINTPTR</type>
          <declname>BaseAddr</declname>
        </param>
        <param>
          <type>u8</type>
          <declname>TmrCtrNumber</declname>
        </param>
        <briefdescription>
<para>This function does a minimal test on the timer counter device and driver as a design example. </para>        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>The purpose of this function is to illustrate how to use the <ref refid="struct_x_tmr_ctr" kindref="compound">XTmrCtr</ref> component in a polled mode.</para><para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>BaseAddr</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>is the base address of the device </para></parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>TmrCtrNumber</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>is the timer counter of the device to operate on. Each device may contain multiple timer counters. The timer number is a zero based number with a range of 0 - (XTC_DEVICE_TIMER_COUNT - 1).</para></parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>XST_SUCCESS to indicate success, else XST_FAILURE to indicate a Failure.</para></simplesect>
<simplesect kind="note"><para>In XSCT/classic flow, DeviceId is used to look up the device configuration. This function contains a loop which waits for the value of a timer counter to change. If the hardware is not working correctly, this function may not return. </para></simplesect>
</para>        </detaileddescription>
